00:01:48.420 --> 00:01:53.300
Arnold Schoenberg, who has
many works I think lodged here

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:57.840
and was commissioned also by the
Library of Congress in his time.

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:04.680
He wrote a book called Style and
Idea, and style is fairly clear.

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:09.040
You can statistically
ascertain, for instance,

00:02:09.040 --> 00:02:11.900
if a play was by Shakespeare
or perhaps by somebody else

00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:15.760
and then put under his name because
there are stylist discrepancies.

00:02:15.760 --> 00:02:18.980
So style is fine, but idea
is a very strange word

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:22.200
when you apply it to the arts.

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:24.700
We don't know in fact,
although books have been written

00:02:24.700 --> 00:02:30.010
on the topic, whether he was
talking about a musical motif,

00:02:30.010 --> 00:02:32.730
about a way of treating
musical motifs.

00:02:32.730 --> 00:02:38.240
We don't know if it was
concrete musical material at all.

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:40.030
Some of his pieces clearly weren't.

00:02:40.030 --> 00:02:45.940 position:56%
I mean, things like Erwartung or Die
gluckliche Hand, the operatic works,

00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:51.490
clearly had a fundamental idea
which by and large I suppose came

00:02:51.490 --> 00:02:55.000
from a mixture of expressionism
and Freudian psychology.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:58.920
But for a composer today,

00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:03.460
it's an issue which is
fraught with problems.

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:08.720
The idea of a piece of music
expressing, incorporating,

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:15.550
articulating an idea or a set
of ideas is problematic simply

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:18.520
because music, although we
can treat it like a language,

00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:20.090
probably is not a language.

00:03:20.090 --> 00:03:24.070 position:56%
It doesn't have the semantic context
that an everyday language has.

00:03:24.070 --> 00:03:27.510
We can't point to things
in music by and large,

00:03:27.510 --> 00:03:31.220
which relate to something
outside music,

00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:33.940
which can be related back
to the inside of music.

00:03:33.940 --> 00:03:36.850
So one of the things
that's concerned me

00:03:36.850 --> 00:03:39.870
over the years has
been the idea indeed

00:03:39.870 --> 00:03:47.470 position:56%
of how much one may derive the
nature of a piece of music from sort

00:03:47.470 --> 00:03:52.930
of act of prior conceptualization,
yes?

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:56.130
And over the years, I've done this.

00:03:56.130 --> 00:04:00.540
I started composing some from
the late '50's and by the time

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:05.890
of the mid '60's, early
'70's, I was writing works

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:12.300
which in some way tried to reflect
bodies of ideas, if you like,

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:16.620
intellectual or [inaudible]
disciplines.

00:04:16.620 --> 00:04:19.770
They could be historic.

00:04:19.770 --> 00:04:22.400
They could be philosophical.

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:26.420
They could be something else
indeed, poetry or what have you,

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:29.550
but I've always felt that
contemporary music suffers

00:04:29.550 --> 00:04:34.240
in many respects by being the
art which does not relate easily

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:40.120
to the everyday sensations,
which we are a party to.

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:45.360
And so we find contemporary
music more difficult to enter

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:50.820
into precisely because we have
to make certain presuppositions,

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:55.880
which A, we are not on the
whole used to doing, and B,

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:57.970
without knowing if
those presuppositions

00:04:57.970 --> 00:05:02.380
that one's making have anything
to do with that piece, in reality.

00:05:02.380 --> 00:05:08.990
So, I've always looked to see if I
can find something in other areas,

00:05:08.990 --> 00:05:17.330
which one can, one can focus
on, one can sit on or stand on,

00:05:17.330 --> 00:05:23.620
one can circle around it, rather
like an artificial flat earth,

00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:26.560
which is sitting on
top of a tortoise,

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:29.690
which is sitting on
top of an elephant.

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:35.180
[laughter] Of course these
things are always not [inaudible]

00:05:35.180 --> 00:05:39.310
arbitrary, but these things are
a reflection of one's own unease

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:42.490
about the means with
which one works.

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:46.590
And part of the drama of
contemporary music in my view

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:52.190
at least since the '70's perhaps
has been understanding how much the

00:05:52.190 --> 00:05:57.170
sociology of musical
creation is involved

00:05:57.170 --> 00:06:01.990
in the actual creation
of musical works.

00:06:01.990 --> 00:06:10.730
Many works have for instance some
sort of improvisatory aspects

00:06:10.730 --> 00:06:13.970
to them, which implies that
the person performing the work,

00:06:13.970 --> 00:06:24.500
the mediator, is aware of the
unspoken criteria of rectitude,

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:28.400
if you like, which he has to apply

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:30.980
to an authentic performance
of the work.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:34.930
And so most of my work,
certainly the last ten years,

00:06:34.930 --> 00:06:39.730
have been based upon
ideas of this [inaudible],

00:06:39.730 --> 00:06:43.750
which can in part be
transcribed into musical means,

00:06:43.750 --> 00:06:49.120
