00:23:23.850 --> 00:23:27.420
and so I guess I'm wondering
if you could say a few words

00:23:27.420 --> 00:23:32.090
about your experience as a former
[inaudible] and how that impacted.

00:23:32.090 --> 00:23:33.390
&gt;&gt; Brian Ferneyhough:
Well it's strange really.

00:23:33.390 --> 00:23:37.280
The flute has always
been an instrument

00:23:37.280 --> 00:23:40.290
that I've written most
for, I suppose,

00:23:40.290 --> 00:23:44.090 position:56%
[inaudible] there have been, I don't
know, seven or eight [inaudible]

00:23:44.090 --> 00:23:46.960
or piece with significant
flute in it anyway.

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:48.760
I never had a lesson in
my life on the flute.

00:23:48.760 --> 00:23:51.410
I learned it, I picked
it up myself at school.

00:23:51.410 --> 00:23:55.260
There was a heap of
military band equipment,

00:23:55.260 --> 00:23:59.750
which my music teacher had
piled, he used to be the director

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:04.240
of the lyrical band in
the wartime circumstances,

00:24:04.240 --> 00:24:08.340
and he piled all these
instruments, which were broken.

00:24:08.340 --> 00:24:11.630
They were sometimes old with
half the keys missing [inaudible]

00:24:11.630 --> 00:24:14.720
or models which no longer
were being built anyway.

00:24:14.720 --> 00:24:18.410
And I went in there, and I took
a flute, and I took an oboe,

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:21.430
and I took a clarinet, and
I stuck them together again,

00:24:21.430 --> 00:24:22.730
and I repaired them.

00:24:22.730 --> 00:24:25.200
I put rubber bands where
I couldn't find springs.

00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:28.670 position:56%
And I started learning to play them.

00:24:28.670 --> 00:24:31.630
And the reason that,
well, this funny thing

00:24:31.630 --> 00:24:35.160
about Cassandra Dream Song, this is
my first flute solo piece I wrote

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:39.760
in 1970, I had just moved
from England to Switzerland.

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:41.660
I was living in the town of Basel.

00:24:41.660 --> 00:24:45.730
And I only had a very
small room, of course.

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:49.190
I was a graduate student at
that time in the [inaudible],

00:24:49.190 --> 00:24:55.410
and the flute was the
only instrument

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:57.920
that realistically I
could take with me.

00:24:57.920 --> 00:25:02.770 position:56%
No piano, no trumpet, which was my
other instrument, and so when I came

00:25:02.770 --> 00:25:05.460
to start a new piece it was
obvious that I did on the basis

00:25:05.460 --> 00:25:06.760
of the instrument that
I had available,

00:25:06.760 --> 00:25:08.730
and I could work everything out.

00:25:08.730 --> 00:25:11.140
And in fact, it was
that particular piece,

00:25:11.140 --> 00:25:13.720
you shouldn't be too impressed
by my picking up the instrument

00:25:13.720 --> 00:25:17.780 position:56%
and playing it for someone else,
it's the only one of my flute pieces

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:22.310
that in fact I could ever play.

00:25:22.310 --> 00:25:23.610
[laughter]

00:25:23.610 --> 00:25:25.620
&gt;&gt; David Phylar: Did that
knowledge kind of set the tone

00:25:25.620 --> 00:25:29.900
for how you would approach dealing,
coming to intimate knowledge

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:32.360
of each instrument that you
write for, because it seems

00:25:32.360 --> 00:25:35.320
like that's just something
that you very clearly possess.

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:37.450 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Brian Ferneyhough: Well you can't
write difficult music unless you

00:25:37.450 --> 00:25:39.940
know what the degree of difficulty
is that you're asking people

00:25:39.940 --> 00:25:43.590
to deal with, both the
conductor and the performers.

00:25:43.590 --> 00:25:47.590
If you can't tell an oboe
player or a trombone player,

00:25:47.590 --> 00:25:52.040
try this position instead
of that position,

00:25:52.040 --> 00:25:54.880
it means you haven't done
your homework essentially,

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:58.110
and many things, by learning
instrumental technique very

00:25:58.110 --> 00:26:01.400
precisely, many things become
available, become opened up to you,

00:26:01.400 --> 00:26:02.740
that wouldn't have been obvious

00:26:02.740 --> 00:26:07.970
if you just followed the
basic trail most travelled.

00:26:13.110 --> 00:26:16.270
&gt;&gt; David Phylar: I think one thing
that I'm always just interested

00:26:16.270 --> 00:26:20.050
in asking composers is what they're
up to now and what they might be,

00:26:20.050 --> 00:26:25.330
what's on the horizon, and maybe
there's another theatrical operatic

00:26:25.330 --> 00:26:27.850
work, and, you know, that sort--

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:29.530
&gt;&gt; Brian Ferneyhough:
What am I doing?

00:26:29.530 --> 00:26:32.580
Well, at my age it's probably
not good to ask people

00:26:32.580 --> 00:26:37.010
to look too far into the future.

00:26:37.010 --> 00:26:41.310
I'm doing a piece based upon a
re-reading of the [inaudible]

00:26:41.310 --> 00:26:44.770
of Christopher Tye, English
Renaissance composer.

00:26:44.770 --> 00:26:47.880
And I'm going to do 10 of those.

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:49.460
I've done several already.

00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:52.390
Each of which will approach
the original material,

00:26:52.390 --> 00:26:56.000
the [inaudible] in a different way.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:02.050
The interesting thing is that these
[inaudible] are totally motile

00:27:02.050 --> 00:27:04.800
[phonetic], they are not
grammatic in any way.

00:27:04.800 --> 00:27:08.020
They don't fit in with
my musical ideas at all.

00:27:08.020 --> 00:27:10.940
So it has been challenging
for me to make each one

00:27:10.940 --> 00:27:14.950
of these little pieces, and
it's re-reading of the original

00:27:14.950 --> 00:27:20.720
if I am using [inaudible],
examine different aspects

00:27:20.720 --> 00:27:23.780
of the original than
one might expect.

00:27:23.780 --> 00:27:28.480
For instance, the one I'm
doing now is for solo cello,

00:27:28.480 --> 00:27:31.540
and what I did was, the
only thing that I take

00:27:31.540 --> 00:27:34.630
from the original is the innominate
dominate [phonetic] thing,

00:27:34.630 --> 00:27:38.150
which [inaudible], and I
counted up all the notes

00:27:38.150 --> 00:27:40.040
that occurred [inaudible]
so a lot of notes.

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:44.590
And I counted up all the notes
in every measure, and the number

00:27:44.590 --> 00:27:49.490
of notes in every measure went from
three to like 17 and back again.

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:56.210
I used that as an input instruction
for how many notes would follow one

00:27:56.210 --> 00:27:59.870
of the innominate dominate pitches.

00:27:59.870 --> 00:28:03.810
So you get a pitch, and then you
get a flurry of other pitches,

00:28:03.810 --> 00:28:05.310
it doesn't matter how
they're created,

00:28:05.310 --> 00:28:07.850
say 15 because that
measure has 15 notes in it.

00:28:07.850 --> 00:28:10.560
Now that's got nothing to
do whatsoever with the music

00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:16.450
of Christopher Tye apart from
in a very, very density way,

00:28:16.450 --> 00:28:19.410
as you know with polyphonic
music of that sort,

00:28:19.410 --> 00:28:20.770
it will start with a few notes.

00:28:20.770 --> 00:28:24.490
It will build up, typically
I measured 30 or something

00:28:24.490 --> 00:28:27.160
to a very high density and
then it will fall off again

00:28:27.160 --> 00:28:29.010
to a slightly less
density at the end,

00:28:29.010 --> 00:28:30.770
and these things happen
all the time.

00:28:30.770 --> 00:28:34.820
So at least I knew that I
would have a sort of curve

00:28:34.820 --> 00:28:37.560
of densities to work with.

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:38.860
&gt;&gt; David Phylar: So
what seemed like a,

00:28:38.860 --> 00:28:43.290
might seem like an arbitrary
thing actually has this very clear

00:28:43.290 --> 00:28:46.430
projection into what the
possibilities are as your--

00:28:46.430 --> 00:28:47.730
&gt;&gt; Brian Ferneyhough: Yeah,

00:28:47.730 --> 00:28:49.030
and every one of the pieces
does something different,

00:28:49.030 --> 00:28:53.760
so it's like one of those old,
those old pinball machines.

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:57.420
If you're very skilled at it,
you can get more money out of it

00:28:57.420 --> 00:28:59.400
or points out of it
than everybody else.

00:28:59.400 --> 00:29:01.510
And that's what we try to do.

00:29:01.510 --> 00:29:06.100
We try to, composers try to
created elevated pinball machines.

00:29:06.100 --> 00:29:07.400
[laughter].

00:29:07.400 --> 00:29:10.940
&gt;&gt; David Phylar: What's your
