00:29:16.300 --> 00:29:24.260
&gt;&gt; David Phylar: Is there a
chance that you'll be working

00:29:24.260 --> 00:29:26.270
on another theatrical
project down the road,

00:29:26.270 --> 00:29:28.690
another opera or something along--

00:29:28.690 --> 00:29:31.640 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Brian Ferneyhough: Nobody's asked
me for one, and nobody had asked me

00:29:31.640 --> 00:29:33.800
for one when I sat down
to write my first one.

00:29:33.800 --> 00:29:36.090
I have to explain that my first
one was like 10 years ago,

00:29:36.090 --> 00:29:39.770
and it was a piece called
Shadowtime, and it was in fact done

00:29:39.770 --> 00:29:42.520
in New York around that period.

00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:45.470 position:56%
And it deals with the life and death

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:49.530
of the German Jewish
philosopher, Walter Benjamin.

00:29:49.530 --> 00:29:53.770
He has always been someone I've
felt some sort of affinity for.

00:29:53.770 --> 00:29:58.720
He was a very chaotic individual in
his life, if not in his thinking.

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:01.630
And, I was always proud of the fact

00:30:01.630 --> 00:30:03.710
that this opera is probably
the only one ever written

00:30:03.710 --> 00:30:09.510
